 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zerlatikflaimweaver>Zerlatik Flaimweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 131<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/9/03 4:42 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Magicians want concussion</span><hr size=1> Well, let me start off by stating that I haven't made any high end PoP/VT forays, so I can't judge mage aggro beyond the high end Velious encounters, but from what I have seen, I don't think mages are having massive difficulties across the board on aggro.  If I had seen this, then I would support giving them the concussion line in a reduced form.  I say reduced because if they had the full strength, they'd be encroaching into our domain in terms of short term DPS, and unneccesarily blurring class lines.  Mages have been, and still are my favorite class to duo or group with, but I don't see the point in making them more mana focussed as a class.<br>
<br>
What I think might be more useful to mages from my own experience duoing and grouping with them is:<br>
<br>
1. The promised pathing upgrade we've seen mentioned in the fanfaires and SOE newsletter.  <br>
<br>
Read through the myriad of threads on why mages want root again.  Sure, a lot of them are from players who never bothered to learn what they can handle and now demand that they have a way out if things go wrong.  On the other hand, most of the ones I pay attention to as having some real issues are the notions of splitting mobs and having pulls take odd paths to create trains the mage can't possibly deal with.  This is a problem that affects all pet classes in some way, if SOE fixes it so mobs took direct routes, player deaths would go down, and there wouldn't be as much of an uproar about root.<br>
<br>
2.  Give pets a higher taunt skill rating.  <br>
<br>
The mages, (and by relation other pet classes), suffer from using pets because they aren't the side of the team that can take a few hits from a mob without crumbling.  If spells are causing more aggro than necessary, give the pets a higher taunt rating to compensate.  Keep the aggro where it belongs.<br>
<br>
3.  Upgrade pets so that when /pet taunt is off, pets generate less aggro than they are now.  <br>
<br>
This way, if you aren't using the pet as a solo tank, the mage doesn't take in nearly as much aggro.  This also means that pets don't end up as near to the top of rampage lists as they have been unless the mage wants them to be there.  You can't tell me that King Tormax sees a wimpy earth pet as a bigger threat than the 8 tanks with primals that are also engaging him.  Or the Sorcerer dropping giantbanes on his butt, for that matter.<br>
<br>
I'm gonna fall back on the standard line here, I don't think mages are broken.  If anything, they're fixed better than I am in certain situations.  What are broken however, are AGGRO and PATHING.  Pathing's been screwed up since release, and I have hope that the promised change will happen, since the engine and other upgrades have changed enough coding to allow these tweaks.  Aggro on the other hand, has been screwy for a while, across the board.  You only notice it more in endgame encounters because the stakes are higher.  The last Vindi raid I did, I managed to get summoned after only one spell cast, a Concussion.  I only cast that at 75 percent, and only to double check his hp before I was gonna start nuking.  With the good 20 players on him hacking away, my little aggro reduction spell shouldn't have pissed him off that much.  I've seen it happen on other mobs, both grouping and raiding, as well.  Hopefully, with the broken aggro post patch we're seeing now, SOE will more tempted to look at the coding and simplify or update it.  <br>
<br>
If changes like I suggested are looked at and implemented, and mages are still catching unfair beatdowns at the end game encounter stage, then I would support giving them some kind of concussion line.  Say 50% of our spell at lvl 55 and researchable, plus a 50% Ancient Greater at 60.  Before that level, they don't seem to need any major help beyond what other pet classes need.  If push comes to shove though, I'd be much more likely to get behind a movement to change the archaic code than mess with class balance any more than it is.<br>
<br>
Baron Zerlatik Flaimweaver<br>
Sorcerer of Tholuxe Paells<br>
